Introduction

This dataset was downloaded from kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/uciml/adult-census-income and the source is a 1994 Census bureau database by Ronny Kohavi and Barry Becker (Data Mining and Visualization, Silicon Graphics). The prediction task of this dataset is to determine whether a person makes over 50.000\(\$\) a year. Developing an algorithm to predict whether a person will earn more than 50.000\(\$\) per year can be useful in several fields such as human resources, to determine if a candidate has the potential to reach a good salary, market segmentation for customizing their marketing and sales strategies to reach that specific segment of the population, personal financial planning, public policy and taxation, as well as economic research.

Description of the features of the dataset:

age: Age of each individual in years

workclass: Working class of the individual. Nominal categorical variable with categories: Private, Self-emp-not-inc, Self-emp-inc, Federal-gov, Local-gov, State-gov, Without-pay, Never-worked.

fnlwgt: Represents weighted estimates of the US civilian non institutional population, derived from the Current Population Survey (CPS) files. These weights are adjusted based on demographic characteristics such as age, sex, race, and Hispanic origin to ensure representative sampling within each state.

education: Level of education in ascending order. Categorical ordinal feature with the following categories: Bachelors, Some-college, 11th, HS-grad, Prof-school, Assoc-acdm, Assoc-voc, 9th, 7th-8th, 12th, Masters, 1st-4th, 10th, Doctorate, 5th-6th, Preschool.

education.num: The level of education of the individual codified as an integer.

marital.status: Indicates the marital state of the individual. Categorical nominal variable with categories: Married-civ-spouse, Divorced, Never-married, Separated, Widowed, Married-spouse-absent, Married-AF-spouse.

occupation: Working sector or area of the individual (categorical nominal variable)

relationship: Closest relative in the family. Categorical nominal variable with categories: Not-in-family ,Unmarried, Own-child, Other-relative

sex: Gender of the person (categorical nominal variable)

capital.gain: Represents the financial gains obtained by the individual (numeric variable)

capital.loss: Represents the financial losses obtained by the individual (numeric variable)

hours.per.week: The weekly work hours of the individual (numeric variable)

native.country: Country where the person was born (categorical nominal variable)

income: Target variable with categories: â<=50Kâ, â50>=kâ

The dataset consists of 32561 observations and 15 attributes. As some of the categorical variables are codified as characters, we codify them as factors, including the target variable. Before codifying the variables, it is important to realize that features: âoccupationâ,âworkclassâ and ânative.countryâ have â?â values, so we replace them by NA:

#Change ? by NAS
df$workclass[df$workclass == '?'] = NA
df$occupation[df$occupation == '?'] = NA
df$native.country[df$native.country == '?'] = NA
#Codify the variables as factors
df$workclass <- factor(df$workclass)
df$education <- factor(df$education)
df$marital.status <- factor(df$marital.status)
df$occupation <- factor(df$occupation)
df$relationship <- factor(df$relationship)
df$sex <- factor(df$sex)
df$income <- factor(df$income)
df$race <- factor(df$race)
df$native.country <- factor(df$native.country)

In the dataset, there are 2 features called âeducationâ and âeducation.numâ, which represent the same information but encoded in a different way. We will keep âeducation.numâ, but encoded as a factor, since it this variable can take only 16 different values.

EDA and preprocessing

In order to build ML algorithms, the dataset is split into train and test. As the dataset is relatively big, 70% of the data is allocated as training and the 30% left is allocated as test.

train_index <- createDataPartition(df$income, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
train <- df[train_index, ]
test <- df[-train_index,]

North America: United-States, Canada

As the variables âmarital.statusâ and ârelationshipâ look similar, we carry out a \(\chi^2\) test to check if there is an association between these \(2\) variables.

contingency_table <- table(train$marital.status, train$relationship)
print(contingency_table)
##             
##              Not-in-family Other-relative Own-child Spouse Unmarried
##   Not spouse          5810            600      3500      0      2391
##   Spouse                 9             84        80  10319         0
chisq.test(contingency_table)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  contingency_table
## X-squared = 22145, df = 4, p-value < 2.2e-16

By looking at the contingency table and from the p-value obtained in the \(\chi^2\) test, there is clear evidence of association between these 2 categorical variables. As the aim of this project is to predict the output with the highest performance possible, we will keep both features in the dataset.

Numerical variables

To better understand the distribution and correlation among numerical variables, we present a pairs plot depicting all the numeric features. Additionally, we utilize colors to differentiate whether the income is greater or smaller than 50.000\(\$\).

numeric_columns <- c('age','fnlwgt','capital.gain','capital.loss',
                    'hours.per.week')
ggpairs(data = train , columns = numeric_columns, aes(color = income))

We complement the pairs plot with a correlation heatmap.

ggcorr(train[,numeric_columns], label = TRUE)

From the pairs plot and the correlation heatmap, it is evident that the correlation among pairs of numerical variables is very low, almost approaching zero. Furthermore, we can derive some interesting insights from the pairs plot. For instance, the feature âageâ seems to play a significant role in determining wealth status, which aligns with logical expectations. Typically, younger individuals tend to earn lower salaries initially, but as they gain experience and age, their earning potential tends to increase. Additionally, as expected, the probability of earning more than 50.000\(\$\) per year increases with the number of working hours per week. However, the peak is reached somewhere between 40 and 50 hours per week.

As observed in the pairs plot, the features âcapital.gainâ and âcapital.lossâ are highly skewed to the right. Therefore, we analyze them in more detail by examining their histograms.

Machine Learning algorithms

As seen before, determining if an individual earns more than \(50.000\$\) annually can be important several applications such as economic research and statistical studies about the population. In those cases, it is important to train a model as much accurate as possible, so in this section, we focus on training models focusing on maximizing the accuracy.

Logistic regression

Before training any supervised ML algorithm, first of all, we fit a logistic regression model and set the results as a benchmark to asses the performance of the future ML algorithms. As seen in the EDA section, the dimension of the dataset is not very high and the correlation among the predictors is low, so we fit a logistic regression model without penalization. One of the advantages of logistic regression compared to more shophisticated ML algorithms is that is easy to explain and to interpret.

#Change the names of the factors to compute the probabilities
#as we want to exctract the probabilities we change the names of the levels of
#target variable
levels(train$income) <- c("under50K", "over50K")
levels(test_imputed$income) <- c("under50K", "over50K")

#Standardize the variables of the dataset for some ML algorithms. Standardize them only using the training data in order to avoid data leakage
preprocessor <- preProcess(train[, numeric_columns], method = c("center", "scale"))
train[, numeric_columns] <- predict(preprocessor, train[, numeric_columns])
test_imputed[, numeric_columns] <- predict(preprocessor, test_imputed[, numeric_columns])
logit_model <- glm(income ~., family = 'binomial', data = train)

KNN

The first ML algorithm is KNN, which is not very suitable for this dataset, since most of the features are categorical and the numerical ones are not related to geospatial data. As KNN is a ML algorithm sensitive to the scale of the features, it is advisable to scale them before training the model. In this case, the variables were standardized at the beginning of this section.

knn_model <- kknn(income ~ ., train = train, test = test_imputed, k = 5)

To improve the model,we perform hyperparameter tunning on the number of neighbors \(k\), the type of distance that is computed, and the distribution of the weights assigned to each neighbor:

control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5, classProbs = TRUE)

#grid for the searching hyperparameters
grid <- expand.grid(kmax = c(5,7,9,11,13,15,17),
                    distance = c(1,2,3),
                    kernel = c('rectangular', 'gaussian'))

#search of hyperparameters with crossvalidation
knn_model_hpo <- train(income ~ ., 
                   data = train, 
                   method = "kknn", 
                   trControl = control,
                   tuneGrid = grid,
                   metric = 'Accuracy')


# Make predictions on the test data
predictions_knn_hpo <- predict(knn_model_hpo, newdata = test_imputed)

#confusion matrix of the model
conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(data = predictions_knn_hpo, reference = test_imputed$income)

The hyperparameters obtained are \(k = 17\), \(p=1\) which corresponds to compute the manhattan distance between points and a rectangular distribution for the weights which means that all the neighbors are given the same weight. Radial kernel:

A radial kernel SVM transforms data into a high-dimensional space using a radial basis function such as a Gaussian function to compute the similarity between pairs of observations, with a parameter \(\gamma = \frac{1}{\sigma}\) controlling the flexibility of the model by adjusting the smoothness of the decision boundary. By default, \(\sigma = 0.1\)

svm_radial_model <- svm(income ~., data = train, kernel = 'radial')

#grid parameter

Random forest

Random Forest algorithm usually works very well as a classifying ML algorithm for tabular data. It generates quasi independent random decision trees via bootstrap aggregation (bagging) and it classifies a class as the most voted one. The main hyperparameters are: the number of trees (ntree) and the number of variables fed to each tree (mtry) First, we will train a random forest model using randomForest() library, which uses the default values \(ntry = \sqrt{p}\) where \(p\) is the number of predictor variables (in this case, \(p=13\)) and \(ntree =500\).

Variable importance of random forest predictions and interpretation of the variables

Explainable Random Forest (ERF) is a variant of the Random Forest algorithm designed to enhance model interpretability. It achieves this by employing techniques such as feature weighting, simplified tree structures, and providing feature importance metrics and local explanations. ERF aims to maintain high predictive performance while improving model transparency, making it useful for applications requiring explainability. For understanding better the performance of random forest algorithm applied to this particular dataset, we show a graph with the most âimportantâ features of the model:

Xgboost

XGBoost (Extreme Gradient Boosting) is an ensemble learning algorithm that combines multiple weak learners, typically decision trees, to create a powerful predictive model. It sequentially builds trees, with each subsequent tree correcting the errors made by the previous ones. Unlike Random Forest, which builds trees independently, XGBoost optimizes the overall performance by penalizing complexity, thereby reducing overfitting and improving predictive accuracy. XGBoost, on the contrary to random forest, has many hyperparameters and it is necessary to tune them in order to avoid overfitting. Since training an XGBoost model is computationally expensive, we directly search for optimal hyperparameters. Due to time constraints, we will focus our grid search on parameters such as ntrees, max_depth, and eta, which controls the learning rate in the boosting process.

# Define the training control
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv",    
                     number = 5, classProbs = TRUE)     

# Define the grid of hyperparameters to search
# Here we'll search over a range of values for nrounds
grid <- expand.grid(nrounds = c(10,50,100,200,500,1000),
                    max_depth = c(3,5,7,9),
                    eta = c(0.01,0.1,0.3),
                    gamma = 0,
                    colsample_bytree = 1,
                    min_child_weight = 1,
                    subsample = 1)

# Train the model with hyperparameter tuning
xgb_model <- train(income ~ .,
                   data = train,
                   method = "xgbTree",
                   trControl = ctrl,
                   tuneGrid = grid,
                   verbosity = 0)

predictions_xgb <- predict(xgb_model,newdata = test_imputed)
conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(data = predictions_xgb, reference = test_imputed$income)
#plot the confusion matrix and several quantities
conf_matrix_table <- as.data.frame(conf_matrix$table)


ggplot(conf_matrix_table, aes(x = Reference, y = Prediction,fill= Freq)) +
        geom_tile() + geom_text(aes(label=Freq)) +
        scale_fill_gradient(low="white", high="#009194") +
        labs(x = "Reference",y = "Prediction") +
        scale_x_discrete(labels=c("<=50K",">50K")) +
        scale_y_discrete(labels=c("<=50K", ">50K")) +
        ggtitle("Confusion Matrix") +
        theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) 

#dataframe with some metrics
metrics_df <- data.frame(
  Value = c(conf_matrix$byClass["Sensitivity"], 
            conf_matrix$byClass["Specificity"],
            conf_matrix$overall["Kappa"],
            conf_matrix$overall["Accuracy"])
)

#optimal hyperparameters
xgb_model$bestTune
##    nrounds max_depth eta gamma colsample_bytree min_child_weight subsample
## 34     200         5 0.1     0                1                1         1
#show the dataframe
print(metrics_df)
##                 Value
## Sensitivity 0.9463323
## Specificity 0.6432823
## Kappa       0.6299415
## Accuracy    0.8733620

The optimal hyperparameters are \(ntrees = 200\), \(eta = 0.1\) and \(max_{depth} = 5\). It can be seen that, unlike in random forest, the performance of the model does not necessarily improve adding more number of trees.

Neural Networks

Neural networks are a class of machine learning algorithms that consist of interconnected nodes, or neurons, organized in layers. Each neuron applies a nonlinear transformation to its inputs and passes the result to neurons in the next layer. Through a process called backpropagation, neural networks adjust the weights of connections between neurons to minimize a defined loss function, enabling them to learn complex patterns and relationships in data. Theyâre characterized by their ability to approximate arbitrary functions and are widely used in various domains for tasks such as regression, classification, and reinforcement learning. For this particular case, we will train a Neural Network with one single hidden layer:

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv",    
                     number = 5, classProbs = TRUE)  

#neural network with one hidden layer
nn_model <- train(income ~., 
                  method = "nnet", 
                  data = train,
                  MaxNWts = 1000,
                  maxit = 100,
                  tuneGrid = expand.grid(size=c(2,4,6), decay=c(0.01,0.001)), 
                  metric = "Accuracy",
                  trControl = ctrl,
                  trace = FALSE)

predictions_nn <- predict(nn_model,newdata = test_imputed)
conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(data = predictions_nn, reference = test_imputed$income)
#plot the confusion matrix and several quantities
conf_matrix_table <- as.data.frame(conf_matrix$table)


ggplot(conf_matrix_table, aes(x = Reference, y = Prediction,fill= Freq)) +
        geom_tile() + geom_text(aes(label=Freq)) +
        scale_fill_gradient(low="white", high="#009194") +
        labs(x = "Reference",y = "Prediction") +
        scale_x_discrete(labels=c("<=50K",">50K")) +
        scale_y_discrete(labels=c("<=50K", ">50K")) +
        ggtitle("Confusion Matrix") +
        theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) 

#dataframe with some metrics
metrics_df <- data.frame(
  Value = c(conf_matrix$byClass["Sensitivity"], 
            conf_matrix$byClass["Specificity"],
            conf_matrix$overall["Kappa"],
            conf_matrix$overall["Accuracy"])
)

#Show the metrics

## Specificity 0.6160714
## Kappa       0.5780933
## Accuracy    0.8543202

The accuracy and the rest of metrics are slightly better than in the logistic regression model but worse than the ones predicted by random forest and xgboost.

Now, we train a deep neural network which in theory will yield to better results that a neural network with one single hidden layer but are more likely to produce overfitting. In this case it will be considered a deep neural network with three layers and we will search for the optimal number of neurons in each layer and the number of iterations over the training set (numepochs)

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv",    
                     number = 5, classProbs = TRUE)  

dnn_model <- train(income ~., 
                  method = "dnn", 
                  data = train,
                  numepochs = 20,
                  tuneGrid = expand.grid(layer1 = 1:10,
                                         layer2 = 0:5,
                                         layer3 = 0:5,
                                         hidden_dropout = 0, 
                                         visible_dropout = 0),
                  metric = "Accuracy",
                  trControl = ctrl)

predictions_dnn <- predict(dnn_model,newdata = test_imputed)
conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(data = predictions_dnn, reference = test_imputed$income)
#plot the confusion matrix and several quantities

Ensemble learning

Finally in order to improve the accuracy, we train an ensemble model. Ensemble is an ML technique that combines the predictions of multiple ML individual models. The idea behind ensemble methods is that by aggregating the predictions of multiple models, the weaknesses of individual models can be compensated for, resulting in improved overall performance. This is the case of some ML algorithms such as random forest or xgboost, which are ensembles of decision trees. In this case, the ensemble is formed by the \(5\) ML algorithms with the highest accuracy: xgb, rf, nn, svm, dnn. The predicted class will be obtained as the mode of the predicted classes by each ML algorithm (majority vote).

#Create a function that computes the mode of a vector
mode <- function(v) {
  uniqv <- unique(v)
  uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v, uniqv)))]
}

#Predictions of the ensemble learning method as the majority vote from the selected ML algorithms
ensemble_predictions = apply(data.frame(predictions_xgb,predictions_nn, predictions_svm_hpo, predictions_dnn, predictions_rf_hpo), 1, mode) 

#The variable ensemble predictions is codified as a character so we codify it as a factor
ensemble_predictions <- factor(ensemble_predictions, levels = levels(test_imputed$income))
conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(data = ensemble_predictions, reference = test_imputed$income)

ROC Curves

In the previous section, we focused on identifying the machine learning method with the highest accuracy, which can be beneficial in various applications such as economic research and statistical analysis. Now, we are comparing the ROC curves of different machine learning methods, excluding SVM, where âprobabilitiesâ are not well defined. We are assessing the models based on the Area Under the Curve (AUC), which measures a modelâs ability to distinguish between the classes of the target variable. This evaluation can be particularly useful in scenarios such as income prediction for tax estimates, where governments use income prediction models to estimate future earnings for taxpayers and formulate fiscal policies and budgets accordingly. In such cases, it is crucial to employ a model that accurately distinguishes between individuals earning more than $50,000 to allocate fiscal resources effectively, ensuring fair taxation for those with lower incomes while appropriately taxing higher earners.

Cost sensitive learning

Until now, we have focused on situations in which the best model is the one with the highest accuracy or the highest AUC. Nevertheless, we can consider the problem of predicting if an individual earns more than 50.000\(\$\) from the perspective of a company that wants to advertise an âexpensiveâ product, targeting customers with salaries higher than this amount. For this hypothetical problem, letâs assume that the company wants to send mail advertising its product to individuals who are likely to afford it. We will assume the cost of sending an advertisement is 10\(\$\), and individuals earning more than 50.000\(\$\) annually have a probability of \(p=0.1\) of buying the product. Given that the price of the product is 1000\(\$\), we will attempt to find the optimal threshold to maximize profit from the companyâs perspective.

#Function that computes the cost and the profit for each element of the confusion matrix in function
#of the probability p
compute_profit <- function(p){
  
  #Profit of true negatives:0
  #Profit of false positives: - 10
  #Profit of true positives: p*1000
  #Profit of false negatives: - 10
  profit <- c(0,-20,0, 1000*p - 20)
  return(profit)
  
}
#Set the seed for reproducible results
set.seed(666)
#vector containing the different probability thresholds
thresholds <- seq(0.05,0.95, length = 15)
#number of models that will be trained for each threshold
n_splits = 50
profit <- matrix(0, nrow = n_splits, ncol = length(thresholds))
#To accelerate the computing part, we randomly choose a sample of 1000 observations only
train_subsample <- train[sample(1:1000),]
#loop for all possible thresholds
for(j in 1:length(thresholds)){
  #We do 50 different splits of the training data for each threshold
  for(i in 1:n_splits){
    #A 80-20%
    d = createDataPartition(train_subsample$income, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
    #We define our train_train and train_test samples
    train_train <- train_subsample[d,]
    train_test <- train_subsample[-d,]  
    
    #We train the xgboost model using the hyperparameters obtained with hyperparameter tunning
    best_params <- xgb_model$bestTune

    #return the probabilities
    ctrl <- trainControl(method = "none", classProbs = TRUE)

    #train a model using xgboost with the hyperparameters calculated previously
    xgb_model2 <- train(income ~ .,
                         data = train_train,
                         method = "xgbTree",
                         trControl = ctrl,
                         tuneGrid = expand.grid(nrounds = best_params$nrounds,
                                                max_depth = best_params$max_depth,
                                                eta = best_params$eta,
                                                gamma = best_params$gamma,
                                                colsample_bytree = best_params$colsample_bytree,
                                                min_child_weight = best_params$min_child_weight,
                                                subsample = best_params$subsample)
    )

     #we compute the predicted probabilities
     threshold_probabilities <- predict(xgb_model2, newdata = train_test, type = 'prob')[,2]

     #Use the the threshold to classify the class of the output
    levels_threshold <- levels(train_test$income)
    threshold_classes <- ifelse(threshold_probabilities > thresholds[j], levels_threshold[2],       levels_threshold[1])
    threshold_classes <- factor(threshold_classes, levels = levels_threshold)
    #compute the table with the confusion matrix of the model
    CM = confusionMatrix(threshold_classes, train_test$income)$table
    #update the a_{ij} element of the profit matrix 
    profit[i,j] <- sum(as.vector(CM)*compute_profit(0.1))
  }
}

For each probability threshold, we show a boxplot with the distribution of the companyâs profit

#Boxplot with the results
ggplot(data = data.frame(reps=reshape2::melt(t(profit))$value, 
                         cutoff = factor(rep(thresholds, n_splits), labels = round(thresholds, 2)))) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = cutoff, y = reps), fill = 'deepskyblue3', col = 'black') + 
  labs(x = 'Probability threshold', y = ' company profit ($)') +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 35, size = 10), plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

The optimal threshold corresponds to the value of the probability threshold that lead to the highest median in the profit distribution. In this case, \(p_{op}=0.24\), which is lower than the default probability threshold \(p=0.5\). The reason is that in order to optimize the profit, the company must send advertisement to the most of its potential customers. Nevertheless, the probability threshold cannot be arbitrarily low because if not, they well spend to much sending advertise to individuals who cannot afford their product or they are not interested in it.

Conclusions

The aim of this dataset was to predict whether an individual earns more than 50.000\(\$\) per year or not. To achieve this, several supervised ML algorithms have been trained using hyperparameters obtained in the hyperparameter search. Among all the applied machine learning algorithms, the one with the highest accuracy is XGBoost, followed by Random Forest. Although the accuracy obtained with this method is only 3% higher than that obtained with a logistic regression model, which is more interpretable. To better interpret XGBoost model, a ranking of variable importance and partial influence plots were generated, revealing that the most influential variables in classifying an individual as earning more than 50k are: marital status, capital gains, age, and capital loss. Afterwards, with the âprobabilitiesâ obtained from training the models, ROC curves were plotted, and the AUC was measured, obtaining that the model with the highest AUC is XGBoost and the one with the lowest is the decision tree.

Finally, a hypothetical scenario was presented in which a company wanted to sell a luxury product and, for that purpose, wished to send advertisements to potential customers. Therefore, they needed to correctly identify people who earn more than $50k per year. By iterating over probability thresholds, it was found that the company would achieve maximum profit using a probability threshold of 0.24 to classify the classes, achieving higher specificity than for p=0.5, but with lower sensitivity and accuracy.
